  <h1>How Property Damage Claims Work</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>First-party vs. third-party claims</h2><p>First-party: you claim against your own insurance (collision, comprehensive, homeowners). Subject to your deductible. Third-party: you claim against the at-fault party&rsquo;s liability insurance. No deductible; the at-fault party&rsquo;s insurer pays. Third-party claims also allow for consequential damages (rental car, loss of use) beyond the property&rsquo;s ACV.</p>
  <h2>The valuation process</h2><p>The insurer assigns an adjuster who inspects the damage and calculates ACV or RCV. For total losses, the insurer uses a comparable vehicle/property database. For partial losses, repair estimates from approved shops determine the payout. Always get an independent estimate to verify the insurer&rsquo;s number.</p>
  <h2>Depreciation disputes</h2><p>Request the itemized depreciation worksheet. Challenge depreciation percentages that don&rsquo;t reflect the actual condition of the property. Provide evidence: maintenance records, photos showing pre-loss condition, comparable market prices.</p>
  <h2>Appraisal clause</h2><p>Most property insurance policies have an appraisal clause: if you and the insurer disagree on the value, each appoints an independent appraiser, and a neutral umpire resolves disputes. This is faster and cheaper than litigation and often produces better outcomes for policyholders.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/rcv-vs-acv">RCV vs. ACV</a> and <a href="/guides/diminished-value-claims">diminished value claims</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
